SIMPLE: matadore
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Matadore
<hw>Mat"a*dore</hw>}</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>matador</ets>, prop., a killer, fr.
<ets>matar</ets> to kill, L. <ets>mactare</ets> to sacrifice,
kill.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The killer; the man appointed to kill the
bull in bullfights; a bullfighter; a toreador.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>In the game of quadrille
or omber, the three principal trumps, the ace of spades being the first,
the ace of clubs the third, and the second being the deuce of a black
trump or the seven of a red one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When Lady Tricksey played a four,⟦br⟧
You took it with a <qex>matadore</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>[Skat]</fld> <def>The jack of clubs, or any other
trump held in sequence with it, whether by the player or by his
adversaries.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A certain game of dominoes in which four dominoes
(the 4-3, 5-2, 6-1, and double blank), called <xex>matadors</xex>, may
be played at any time in any way.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matagasse</ent>⟦br⟧
